03833nam a22004695i 9780773596573DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735965737 a10.1515/97807735965732doi  a(DE-B1597)656324  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.C2b.T395 2014 7aPSY0310002bisacsh04a305.8970712231 aTaylor, Donald M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTowards Constructive Change in Aboriginal Communities :bA Social Psychology Perspective /cDonald M. Taylor. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource :b7 b&w photos, 6 diagrams  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tAboriǵinal People and the Canadian Psyche -- tAboriǵinal Voices, Cultural Diversity, and Aboriginal Resilience -- tColonialism’s Legacy: A Litany of Community Challenges -- tCollective Self-Control: Towards an Understanding of Community Challenges -- tCultural Identity Vacuum: The Real Impact of Colonialism -- tThe Normative Structure of Aboriǵinal Communities: When 80–20 Becomes 20–80 -- tTowards Constructive Social Change in Aboriginal Communities: Minority Influence -- tZero Tolerance -- tSurvey Research as a Vehicle for Constructive Community Change -- tTowards Constructive Change in Aboriǵinal Communities: From Theory to Implementation -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe widespread failure of so many interventions in First Nations and Inuit communities across Canada requires an explanation. Applying the theoretical and methodological rigour of experimental social psychology to genuine community-based constructive change, Donald Taylor and Roxane de la Sablonnière outline new ways of addressing the challenges that Aboriginal leaders are vocalizing publicly. To date, the decolonization process in Canada has led to programs that focus on the struggling individual. However, colonization was and still is a collective process and thus requires collective solutions. Rooted in years of research, teaching, and experience in First Nations and Inuit communities, the authors offer necessary solutions. They contend that survey research can be uniquely applied as a means to initiate constructive community change, demonstrating how their intervention process uses such research to foster positive social norms by feeding the results back to the community. Ultimately, Towards Constructive Change in Aboriginal Communities outlines how field research can be used to give a voice to First Nations and Inuit community members and serve as a platform for constructive social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxPsychology. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Social Psychology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359657340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773596573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773596573/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles